 : The culture and identity of casual online play -- t19. Afterplay -- tAbout the authors -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIn Playful Identities, eighteen scholars examine the increasing role of digital media technologies in identity construction through play. Going beyond computer games, this interdisciplinary collection argues that present-day play and games are not only appropriate metaphors for capturing postmodern human identities, but are in fact the means by which people create their identity. From discussions of World of Warcraft and Foursquare to digital cartographies, the combined essays form a groundbreaking volume that features the most recent insights in play and game studies, media research, and identity studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 0aComputer games. 0aVideo gamesxPsychological aspects. 0aVideo gamesxSocial aspects. 7aART / General.2bisacsh1 ade Souza e Silva, Adriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchouten, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCermak-Sassenrath, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMäyrä, Frans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrissen, Valerie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCalleja, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJansz, Jeroen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTimmermans, Jeroen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb